Perceived_purpose1: The purpose of the coin flip game is to try to earn money. The sender knows the outcome. The sender then sends a message to the receiver on the outcome. The receiver can choose to go with the sender's message or not. If the sender wants both themselves and the receiver to succeed, they should give the receiver the WRONG outcome as pay for the receiver is based on whether they are INCORRECT, and 90% of receivers trust the sender.
Perceived_purpose2: The purpose of the rely or verify game also involves trust. The red player knows the outcome. The red player can choose to give the blue player a true or false statement regarding the outcome. If the blue player relies on the red player's word, and the outcome is correct, they both get money. If the red player wants a higher payoff, they can attempt to manipulate the blue player by giving an inaccuracy. If the blue player relies on the red player's word, they will receive nothing, and the red player would receive more than they would had both players profited. Of course, blue player may not trust red player's word and verify it, in which they will lose $0.50 from their pay to do so.

Perceived_purpose1: The coin flip game's purpose is to earn real money by making a choice as to on which side of the coin the flip lands. The sender can either lie or be truthful and the receiver has to make a judgement to believe the sender or not.

Perceived_purpose1: It appears to be a test of game theory where the range of outcomes seemingly favor trying to mislead the other player.  It is about anticipating the move of the other player when there is imperfect information regarding that player's motives and psychology.
Perceived_purpose2: This was testing my level of trust in an anonymous player.  The range of outcomes to me seemed to either require trusting the other player and hoping that the outcome leads to some money for me, or being skeptical of the other player and choosing to verify and win at least something for sure.  I think the main purpose of this game was to test how willing a person is to make risky choices in the hopes of a potentially bigger payout.
